### useEffect

`useEffect` lets you perform side effects in functional components: data fetching, subscriptions, timers, DOM manipulation, and logging.

---

### Syntax

```jsx
useEffect(() => {
  // Side effect code
  return () => {
    // Cleanup code
  };
}, [dependencies]);
```

### Dependency Array Patterns

| Dependency Array | Runs |
|-----------------|------|
| `undefined` | After every render |
| `[]` | Once on mount, cleanup on unmount |
| `[a, b]` | When `a` or `b` changes |

### Common Use Cases

```jsx
// Data fetching
useEffect(() => {
  fetch('/api/users')
    .then(res => res.json())
    .then(data => setUsers(data));
}, []);

// Subscriptions
useEffect(() => {
  const subscription = source.subscribe(data => setData(data));
  return () => subscription.unsubscribe();
}, [source]);

// Timers
useEffect(() => {
  const id = setInterval(() => setTime(new Date()), 1000);
  return () => clearInterval(id);
}, []);
```

### Cleanup Function

Return a function from the effect to clean up subscriptions, timers, or event listeners:

```jsx
useEffect(() => {
  window.addEventListener('resize', handleResize);
  return () => window.removeEventListener('resize', handleResize);
}, []);
```

> **Key Point:** Always specify all reactive values in the dependency array. Use the exhaustive-deps ESLint rule to catch missing dependencies.

codeExample:
import { useEffect, useState } from 'react';

function UserProfile({ userId }) {
  const [user, setUser] = useState(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    let cancelled = false;
    fetch(`/api/users/${userId}`)
      .then(res => res.json())
      .then(data => {
        if (!cancelled) setUser(data);
      });
    return () => { cancelled = true; };
  }, [userId]);

  return user ? <h1>{user.name}</h1> : <p>Loading...</p>;
}
